text.tspan: The radiation considered here is from
cosmic rays. Those have the most
energy by far. Less energetic radiation
mostly doesn't penetrate even the
glass between the beams, but it takes
a full kilogram of material per square
centimeter to block cosmic rays as
much as Earth's atmosphere does.
The damage done by cosmic rays is
fundamentally different than other
radiation. So far, it seems effects of a
year or so exposure in LEO isn't too
dangerous. We can't say for sure until
ISS astronauts get older. Much longer
exposures may be much riskier.
Avg. dose 0.05 Sv/yr
Avg. Dose 0.12 Sv/yr
Avg. Dose 0.03 Sv/yr
Avg. Dose 0.005 Sv/yr
Avg. Dose 0.01 Sv/yr
Less than Earth
Sea Level
In this configuration, radiation above Earth Sea
Level amounts comes from around 1% of the field
of view almost anywhere in the atrium. From that
direction, damaging particles will regularly strike
people, but the rate at which that happens is far
lower than for current ISS astronauts. It is
reasonable to guess that the human body can
repair such damage well enough that there would
be no resulting health risk. But, more study will be
needed to know.
(Above doses are only that due to neutrons
released by the passage of cosmic ray
particles. True dose includes protons and
nuclides and is much higher.)
